Perspectives on Sino-American Relations in 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations unsettled large parts of Asia.
A year ago, U.S. President Donald Trump returned from his particularly grand "State Visit Plus" to Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-Chinese campaign rhetoric would finally become a thing of the past.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are entangled in a trade war, and the Trump administration has replaced the U.S. "strategic engagement" in China with "strategic competition."
This is compounded by the fact that the U.S., European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
There is great uncertainty in the financial markets today, with growth slowing in China and Europe, and in America, the higher interest rates are starting to take effect.
The uncertainty regarding the future development of nuclear talks with North Korea also clouds the picture.
What are therefore the prospects for the relations between the United States and China in 2019?
It is likely that by March, an agreement on the reduction of the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions China will make in this regard will be reached.
An agreement on tariff reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the targeted timeframe.
If one tariff after another were negotiated, a year could pass.
However, if Chinese economic reformers were to adopt a more drastic approach by, over time, committing to the abolition of all tariffs and urging Americans to follow suit, a quicker outcome could result.
That would certainly displease Chinese trade officials, who have been trained for decades to give little, let alone everything, all at once.
The reform of the so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively straightforward.
Nevertheless, a reform is something else than the way contractual agreements might be interpreted in practice, even if there should be no specific provisions regarding technology transfer.
The protection of intellectual property is, however, extremely problematic.
Previous agreements made under the administration of President Barack Obama could be reconfirmed.
Their enforcement or legal action in cases of infringement of intellectual property rights remains, however, a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism involves subjecting relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international trade arbitration institutions based in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically tasked with enforcing the protection of intellectual property rights.
If China raises objections, it could develop its own international trade arbitration procedure based in China.
For that, however, it would have to call upon qualified foreigners to join its arbitration panel in order to strengthen international credibility.
No one trusts Chinese commercial courts.
For its own internal reform needs, China must move toward completely independent commercial and civil chambers within its judicial system, even though the criminal chamber remains under political control.
The United States' concerns regarding state subsidies under China's "Made in China 2025" strategy are unlikely to be easily resolved.
The fact is that all countries provide a certain level of state support to their domestic technology sectors, although this is highest in China.
Even if we prescribed the maximum level of government support for a particular company, it would be difficult to assess compliance.
I am not confident that there will be an agreement in this area.
Perhaps America simply has to outmaneuver China by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China offers customs reforms to the rest of the international community.
So could China, over time, decide to take this drastic step not only with the United States, but also to agree on tariff-free trade with all member states of the World Trade Organization.
In this way, China was presented with a nearly irresistible opportunity to position itself as a defender of global free trade and to curb the trend toward protectionism.
In the context of such a shift, China could request the member states of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) to join, in order to overtake the United States (which had withdrawn from the trade agreement as one of Trump's first official actions) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably agile when it discovers a political opening and market opportunity.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations regarding China's accession to the TPP have decreased since the recent visit of Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges in relation to the United States, China is likely to be committed in 2019 to reducing conflicts in its relations with other countries within its general foreign and security policy.
In relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from Japan's Coast Guard suggests a significant decrease in Chinese incursions into the territory of the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China also aims to reduce tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) over the South China Sea by accelerating negotiations on a "Code of Conduct."
In addition, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India after the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could start to moderate its stance toward Taiwan, in light of the electoral defeat suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party, the party of Taiwan's President Tsai Ing-wen, which supports independence, in last month's local and regional elections.
This would naturally change radically if the US continues with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
There are still incidents at sea with the United States in the South China Sea, and the conflict could escalate if the United States more strongly emphasizes its stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
Throughout all of Eurasia, China will continue to implement its major project, the "New Silk Road."
However, in recent months, the initiative has not generated as much political attention in China.
Among Chinese officials, there are already discussions about revising certain modalities, following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota Port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns regarding the long-term financial viability of the New Silk Road.
Therefore, in 2019, triumphant reports on the New Silk Road might be less frequent to hear.
In addition, China is likely to strengthen and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than highlighting new institutions of international political action.
He is likely to continue appearing as a new advocate for the WHO and maintain his stance on global climate change, as agreed upon in the 2015 Paris Climate Agreement.
More sober representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it is better to focus on the existing mechanisms of the global rules-based system, especially when the United States consistently shows contempt for them.
While China tries to stabilize its relations with the United States and reduce tensions with other countries, its leadership is likely to use the year 2019 to form a well-informed judgment about the future of U.S. policy: the consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his administration, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new U.S. strategy in any way.
Although they have already come to the conclusion that the United States' stance toward China has undergone a fundamental change, they remain uncertain about the exact form this change takes and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is warranted.
